        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "Subject Pronouns",
        "content": "Subject pronouns tell us WHO is doing the action. Unlike English, Spanish often drops the pronoun because verb endings indicate the subject. However, you need to know them."
      },
      {
        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "The Pronoun Chart",
        "content": "Learn these essential pronouns:\n                              \n   ✏️ Exercise: Which pronoun means 'we'?",
        "examples": [
          {
            "spanish": "yo",
            "english": "I"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "tú",
            "english": "you (informal)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "él",
            "english": "he"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "ella",
            "english": "she"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "usted (Ud.)",
            "english": "you (formal)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "Tú vs Usted",
        "content": "'Tú' is informal — use with friends, family, peers, and children. 'Usted' is formal — use with strangers, elders, and professionals. When in doubt, use 'usted' to show respect."
      },
      {
        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "The Verb SER (To Be)",
        "content": "SER is one of two Spanish verbs meaning 'to be.' Use SER for permanent, essential, or defining characteristics.\n                              \n   ✏️ Exercise: Complete: Yo ___ estudiante. (I am a student)",
        "examples": [
          {
            "spanish": "yo soy",
            "english": "I am"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "tú eres",
            "english": "you are (informal)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "él/ella/usted es",
            "english": "he/she is, you are (formal)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "nosotros somos",
            "english": "we are"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "ellos/ustedes son",
            "english": "they are, you all are"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "When to Use SER",
        "content": "Use SER for: Identity (who someone is), Origin (where from), Profession, Nationality, Physical traits, Personality, Time & dates.\n                              \n   ✏️ Exercise: Complete: Ellos ___ de España.\n\n   ✏️ Exercise: Translate: 'We are students'",
        "examples": [
          {
            "spanish": "Soy María",
            "english": "I am María (identity)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "Soy de México",
            "english": "I am from Mexico (origin)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "Soy profesor",
            "english": "I am a teacher (profession)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "Soy estadounidense",
            "english": "I am American (nationality)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "Ella es alta",
            "english": "She is tall (physical trait)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "Introducing Yourself",
        "content": "Now let's put it together! Here are the essential phrases for self-introduction:\n                        → Soy [profesión] = I am a [profession]",
        "examples": [
          {
            "spanish": "Me llamo [nombre]",
            "english": "My name is [name]"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "Soy de [lugar]",
            "english": "I am from [place]"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "Tengo [número] años",
            "english": "I am [number] years old"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "Soy [profesión]",
            "english": "I am a [profession]"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
